7 Un’aura dolce, sanza mutamento 8 avere in sé, mi feria per la fronte 9 non di più colpo che soave vento;
10 per cui le fronde, tremolando, pronte 11 tutte quante piegavano a la parte 12 u’ la prim’ ombra gitta il santo monte;
13 non però dal loro esser dritto sparte 14 tanto, che li augelletti per le cime 15 lasciasser d’operare ogne lor arte;
16 ma con piena letizia l’ore prime, 17 cantando, ricevieno intra le foglie, 18 che tenevan bordone a le sue rime,
19 tal qual di ramo in ramo si raccoglie 20 per la pineta in su ’l lito di Chiassi, 21 quand’ Ëolo scilocco fuor discioglie.

query.result:
7 A sweet air, without change 8 having in itself, struck me on the forehead 9 not more with a blow than a sweet wind;
10 through which the branches, trembling, ready 11 all bent to the part 12 where the first shadow casts the holy mountain;
13 not however from their being straight separated 14 so much, that the little birds on the tops 15 would leave off practicing every their art;
16 but with full joy the early hours, 17 singing, received among the leaves, 18 which held refrain to its rhymes,
19 just as from branch to branch it gathers 20 through the pine forest up on the shore of Chiassi, 21 when Aeolus loosened the south wind.

